ith the same origin as (1)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William John Harsnet was born in 1510, in Colchester, Essex, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Halsnoth Harsnett, was 30 and his mother, Jeanette Murphy, was 30. He married Elizabeth Jones in 1535, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died on 13 January 1599, in his hometown, at the age of 89."},"et":{"1510–13 Jan 1599":"1510–13. jaanuar 1599","1510–1599":"1510–1599","1520–Female":"1520–Surnud","1522–1640":"1522–1640","1535–Female":"1535–Surnud","1510–1578":"1510–1578","1515–1565":"1515–1565","1530–1620":"1530–1620","1541–1573":"1541–1573","1517–1569":"1517–1569","1480–1565":"1480–1565","1480–1556":"1480–1556","10 November 1573":"10. november 1573","December 1541":"detsember 1541","1480":"1480","1569":"1569","1535":"1535","1556":"1556","1578":"1578","13 Jan 1599":"13. jaanuar 1599","1522":"1522","1599":"1599","1510":"1510",